bioghist.head: History
bioghist.p: Journalist, author. Gay, the son of Ebenezer and Mary Alleyne Otis Gay, was an active abolitionist before and during the Civil War. He edited the ANTI-SLAVERY STANDARD and during the Civil War was managing editor of the NEW YORK TRIBUNE. In 1867 he became managing editor of the CHICAGO TRIBUNE and served on the editorial board of the SATURDAY EVENING POST. He was the author of several books. In 1845 he married Elizabeth Neall of Philadelphia, who was also active in abolitionist work and the woman's rights movement.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Letters written to Gay from political and literary contemporaries such as Horace Greeley, Charles Sumner, and William Bryant; reports in letter form from his reporters at the front during the Civil War; and personal correspondence including many letters from his wife. Letters written to Mrs. Gay from family friends and business associates including many from her husband. Correspondence of other members of the Gay family including Walter Gay, Sarah Gay, and Allan Gay. Diaries, notebooks, and journals of Sydney Howard Gay.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Selected materials cataloged; remainder arranged by category. Boxes 1-71: Cataloged correspondence; Boxes 72-76: Manuscripts & documents; Box 77: Genealogical materials & photographs; Boxes 78-79: Printed materials.

accessrestrict.head: Access Restrictions
accessrestrict.p: Available for faculty, students, and researchers engaged in scholarlyor publication projects.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Identification of specific item; Date (if known); Sydney Howard Gay Papers; Box and Folder (if known); Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Columbia University Library.

userestrict.head: Restrictions on Use
userestrict.p: Reader must use microfilm for incoming and outgoing correspondence for the years 1862-1865, and for correspondence with Maria W. Chapman; Lydis Maria Child; Mary Grew; Edmund Quincy; and Anne, Caroline, Deborah, Lucia, and Emma Weston.
Permission to publish materials must be obtained in writing from the Librarian for Rare Books and Manuscripts.
